value.Title: Planning And Presenting Plant Science Research
Light Microscopy Plant
value.Description: Basic Light Microscopy- Plant.  In this 5-week hands-on basic light microscopy course, participants will learn how to use and care for light and epifluorescence microscopes.  Participants will also learn sample preparation techniques, e.g. GUS staining, image collection methods, e.g., bright-field, dark-field, differential interference contract (DIC/Normaski), and how to collect and assemble publication quality figures.  The goals of the course are that particpants will gain basic skills in light microscopy, and practical knowledge of sample preparation, image collection, preparation of figures for publication.

value.Title: Princ Of Organic Sustain Ag
value.Description: The course will involve lectures and hands-on laboratory exercises in the principles and practices of organic agriculture.  The course is geared for the agriculture and non-agriculture major to understand not only the practices in organic production that lead to a safer food supply but practices that ensure long-term sustainability of agriculture that ensures a productive ecosytem.  Students will learn the basic principles of and regulations governing organic production while learning through laboratory exercises how farmers implement production practices to achieve the principles of the organic approach to agriculture.

value.Title: Applied Plant Genomics
value.Description: This course aims to provide graduate students an introduction to the theory and practice of functional genomics in plants. The course is centered around the many forms in which the newer sequencing technologies are applied to understand plant genomes, their variation and their function. The course will cover concepts in Plant genome sequencing, Transcriptome profiling and Functional enrichment analyses in sets of genes. This is a full-semester course that meets twice a week for: 1. A lecture that covers the rationale and theory of the topic and 2. A hands-on lab section that provides experience with the computational tools and packages used in plant genomics and transcriptomics. The expected course outcomes are A. General knowledge of the theory behind computational tools used in plant genomics; B. Technical knowledge on how to run these tools on a server; and C. Exploring the range of the parameters for each tool and the influence of parameter choices on the outcome.

Turf & Landscape Weed Mgmt
value.Description: Prerequisite: BTNY 304 or as co-requisite Fall 2016. This course is designed to familiarize students to the biology, ecology, and management of weeds associated with managed turfgrass and landscape ecosystems. The course uses a combination of lecture, discussion, laboratory, and field trips to teach the fundamentals of turf and landscape weed identification, ecology, and management. Diverse topics such as the influence of weed control on pollinators and management of native grasses will also be covered. Lectures will introduce concepts and the required readings allow students to gain broader perspective to make the laboratory assignments/activities interactive.

value.Title: Controlled Environment Production Of Horticultural Crops
Ethnic Crops
value.Description: Description to be placed in the Schedule of Classes:  This course will bring a cultural awareness, curiosity to different ethnic crops and role they play in different lives of the consumers. Students will critically analyze the economic, social use of these crops and ways that can be promoted in the US through class discussions, presentations and reflections. Students will have a chance to observe and interact with some of the ethnic crops as a way of bringing knowledge about these crops.

value.Title: Greenhouse & Lands Mgmt For Ed
value.Description: Applying greenhouse and landscape management fundamentals to successfully operate and maintain greenhouses. Laboratories will explore how to identify and produce both woody and herbaceous plants while maintaining and operating greenhouse technologies. Laboratories will also explore how to implement landscape design technologies and identify tools, equipment, and landscape plants. The key focus will be preparing future educators to teach these concepts in the classroom.
